post_text:
LHS 2020 Yearbooks Have Arrived!

We are excited to announce that the 2020 yearbooks have arrived and will be available for pick up this Saturday, Aug. 15, for 2020 graduates only. Underclassmen will receive their books next week.

The distribution will be a drive-thru format. When you come to campus, enter school at the traffic light/main entrance and follow the route to the band door (Door 40) and remain in your car. Have your ID ready, we will scan it, and off you go with a book full of memories! We will distribute books rain or shine.

Pickup will be divided into three groups by your last name:

9:30 a.m.-10:30 a.m. - last names A-F

10:45 a.m.-11:45 a.m. - last names G-P

12:00 p.m.-1:00 p.m. - last names Q-Z

If you are unable to attend distribution you may have a parent or family member pick up with your student ID number. You will not be able to pick up books for your friends.

If you miss this distribution day, we will hold onto the books until we distribute again in November and then again in December.

post_text:
At its July 22, 2020, Special Meeting, the Community High School District 128 Board of Education voted to begin the 2020-2021 school year in remote learning. Named “Extended e-School,” the plan has been designed to enable D128 students and staff to engage in online teaching and learning activities until conditions allow for larger numbers of people to safely return to the buildings.

It is the District’s intent to continue athletics, fine arts and extracurriculars as ISBE/IDPH/IHSA guidance and health conditions allow.

Complete details of the plan will be finalized in the coming weeks and will be shared via a communication hub known as d128 next.

post_text:
Johnny O'Connor Receives Heart of a Champion Award

D128 Special Olympics Athlete Johnny O'Connor received the Jim Rogers Heart of a Champion Award at his home last night. Named in memory of former D128 Special Olympics Coach Jim Rogers, the award is presented to the D128 Special Olympic athlete who best represents the program throughout the year or, like Johnny, who has been in our program for eight years and has grown so much in that time and has made us so proud. Over his eight years on the team, Johnny has competed in soccer, unified soccer, bowling, track, bocce, basketball, floor hockey, and snowshoeing! In addition to his family, D128 representatives joined him for the special presentation. Pictured below at the presentation are (from left) Special Olympics Coach Corey Atwell, Assistant Superintendent Rita Fischer, Board of Education President Pat Groody, Johnny O'Connor, Head Special Olympics Coach Andy Compton and Superintendent Prentiss Lea.

Watch for more Special Olympics end-of-year awards in next week's ePawPrints!

post_text:
LHS Students Receive Poetry and Prose Contest Honors

Five LHS students received honors in the 2019-2020 Illinois Association of Teachers of English (IATE) Poetry and Prose Contest. The following students (pictured below from left) and their submissions were recognized in the IATE's nearly 50-year-old contest, designed to recognize and celebrate the best student writers in the state:

Molly Muscato, "The Keeper"--Winner (Prose)
Celia McDermott-Hinman, "Constant and Unyielding"--Runner Up (Prose)
Charlotte Pulte, "Song of Summer"--Runner Up (Prose)
Elise Stouffer, "Neighbor Sharon, Always Next Door"--Winner (Poetry)
Madelyn Wittenbrink, "1 Poem, or 3"--Winner (Poetry)

Thank you to the students who submitted work, the teachers who nominated students, and Mrs. LeMaistre for overseeing the entire process.

post_text:
Be a Part of the Libertyville Day of Music

Join us for a one-time event on Friday, May 15 at 5:00 p.m.

All local Libertyville musicians are invited to participate on any instrument or voice!

*Invite your local friends and family to participate
*Perform in your front or back yard
*Create an ensemble of your immediate family members and play for your neighbors
*Video yourself/family playing and submit for the Village of *Libertyville Virtual Memorial Day Ceremony

Music will be provided for all abilities.

Let’s unite as a community and share the joy of music to demonstrate our support for our essential workers.

Visit this link to access the music: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FIhfXdwMYblD-6-clchNTsiXv4sMd8yA

Contact Dustin Helvie for more information at
dustin.helvie@d128.org.

post_text:
Need a feel-good moment for today? Enjoy this story and video about the amazing work done by the VHHS student-artists who participated in The Memory Project along with art teacher Allison Molloy:

The VHHS Art Department received a video for The Memory Project portrait delivery to Malaysian children on April 1. The children were so excited to receive our students' artwork, and they fully understood that creating the portraits was a way to show them how much our students care about their well-being and their future during uncertain times.

Our student-artists' efforts show these children that their well-being and future matters. Over 5,000 portraits were flown to Malaysia with members of the non-profit team delivering them before borders were closed and quarantine began. In building this international connection through visual art, VHHS students create to fulfill part of the DARING mission of District 128.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1t3hAEWGwiG8zfLBkcar-m4NAh6iD1DZ3/view?usp=sharing

post_text:
D128 Special Olympians Participate in United Job Shadow Day

On March 3, members of the D128 Special Olympics Team participated in a job shadow day with United Airlines at O'Hare International Airport. Student-athletes Anna Scholler, Alexa Donato, Nathan Ferrara, Eric Eitel, Noah Hewitt, Shaw Keranen, Alex Aquende and Daniel Granados shadowed United employees throughout the day learning how to be an ambassador, check-in and handle luggage, check-in people at the gate and board them, and many other important jobs that take place at United every day. D128Special Olympic coaches and VHHS teachers @Andy Compton and Sean Kelly accompanied the students to O'Hare.

Thank you to the amazing staff at United for hosting this amazing opportunity for our student-athletes!

post_text:
The District 128 Special Olympics Swim Team, Libertyville Stars, is hosting its first disability swim meet at LHS today! Seventy athletes from six teams are competing in the Reach for the Stars meet.

The Libertyville Stars Swim Club is celebrating its 20th season as a team. The Stars Swim Club currently has 31 athletes, ages 13-49 years old, who come from all over Lake County. The team also has nearly as many high school volunteer coaches who are themselves competitive swimmers. The high school volunteers swim with club and high school teams in Lake County including Libertyville HS, Vernon Hills, HS, Mundelein HS, Warren HS, and Highland Park HS. The Stars meet weekly at LHS for Sunday practices and attend numerous swim meets throughout the year, culminating in the IL State Special Olympics Summer Games in Normal, IL.

Good luck to all of today’s competitors and a HUGE thank you to the volunteer students and staff who made the event possible!

VHHS Hosts 6th Annual History Fair

VHHS juniors filled the VHHS LMC with displays and documentaries for the 6th Annual History Fair held yesterday thru today. This year's research projects examined a U.S. history topic that relates to "Breaking Barriers." More than 300 U.S. History students participated in the fair, with the top entrants advancing to the regional and, hopefully, state competition.

shared_text:
District 128 Foundation for Learning
January 27 at 4:31 PM ·

The District 128 Foundation for Learning continued its mission of enhancing learning in Community High School District 128 by awarding DARING Innovation Grants totaling $24,496.58 to Libertyville High School and Vernon Hills High School teachers on Dec. 19. The 2019-20 grants brought the total dollars funded to $242,944.43. In addition, the Foundation has given money to the high schools for project funding and assistance for students in need. To date, the Foundation has given LHS and VHHS $410,847.85 in funding for these initiatives.

Help the Foundation continue its mission to enhance and enrich learning in D128 by supporting the Foundation's first 1-28 Day of Giving. Visit d128.org/foundation to donate today!

post_text:
Storm Blue and Storm Black Capture 2nd @ Area Basketball Tournament

On Sunday, Jan. 12, D128 Special Olympians competed at the Area Basketball Tournament at Hersey High School. Both teams finished 2nd, taking home silver medals. Congratulations to our athletes:

Storm Blue Team - McKenzie Ruhnke, Rithanyaa Venkat, Johnny Oconnor, Shaw Keranen, Hailey Dunbar, Daniel Granados, Albina Giza and Noah Hewitt

Storm Black Team - Nathan Ferrara, Alexa Donato, Anna Scholler, Chris Morozin, Chase Miller, Anthony Berktold and Joseph Maller.

post_text:
LHS Students Attend Midwest Clinic

Members of the LHS Music Department had an opportunity to observe the largest music conference in the world, the Midwest Clinic-International Band and Orchestra Conference, today in Chicago. Students attended clinic sessions and concerts by renowned composers, clinicians, conductors, and music educators. In addition, they visited the exhibits that featured music publication companies, colleges and universities, and instrument manufacturers.
